10 AS INTRODUCED
11 An Act relating to fentanyl overdose and overdose
reporting; requiring first responders to report drug
12 overdose; requiring medical care before reporting;
providing for immunity; amending 63 O.S. 2021,
13 Section 2-401, as last amended by Section 13, Chapter
486, O.S.L. 2025 (63 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 2-401),
14 which relates to prohibited acts; providing
rebuttable prima facie evidence that fentanyl was the
15 proximate cause of death; providing for codification;
and providing an effective date.
16
17
18
19 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
20 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
21 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1-2506.3 of Title 63, unless
22 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
23 A. When any first responder, as defined in section 1-2506.1 of
24 this title, responds to an incident in which the first responder
HB2941 HFLR Page 1
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 reas onably believes a person is experiencing or has experienced a
2 drug overdose, the first responder shall contact local law
3 enforcement as soon as practicable after attending to the medical
4 needs of the person.
5 B. The obligation to contact law enforcement does not require
6 delay in providing medically necessary emergency care.
7 C. A first responder acting in good faith under this section
8 shall be immune from civil or criminal liability for contacting law
9 enforcement.
10 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 63 O.S. 2021, Section 2-401, as
11 last amended by Section 13, Chapter 486, O.S.L. 2025 (63 O.S. Supp.
12 2025, Section 2-401), is amended to read as follows:
13 Section 2-401. A. Except as authorized by the Uniform
14 Controlled Dangerous Substances Act, it shall be unlawful for any
15 person:
16 1. To distribute, dispense, transport with intent to distribute
17 or dispense, possess with intent to manufacture, distribute, or
18 dispense, a controlled dangerous substance or to solicit the use of
19 or use the services of a person less than eighteen (18) years of age
20 to cultivate, distribute or dispense a controlled dangerous
21 substance;
22 2. To create, distribute, transport with intent to distribute
23 or dispense, or possess with intent to distribute, a counterfeit
24 controlled dangerous substance; or
HB2941 HFLR Page 2
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 3. To distribute any imitation controlled substance as defined
2 by Section 2-101 of this title, except when authorized by the Food
3 and Drug Administration of the United States Department of Health
4 and Human Services.
5 B. Any person who violates the provisions of this section with
6 respect to:
7 1. A substance classified in Schedule I or II, except for
8 marijuana, upon conviction, shall be guilty of transporting or
9 possessing with an intent to distribute a controlled dangerous
10 substance, a Class C2 felony offense, and shall be sentenced to a
11 term of imprisonment as provided for in subsections B through F of
12 Section 20M of Title 21 of the Oklahoma Statutes, and a fine not
13 more than One Hundred Thousand Dollars ($100,000.00), which shall be
14 in addition to other punishment provided by law and shall not be
15 imposed in lieu of other punishment. A second conviction for the
16 violation of provisions of this paragraph is a Class C2 felony
17 offense punishable by a term of imprisonment as provided for in
18 subsections B through F of Section 20M of Title 21 of the Oklahoma
19 Statutes. A third or subsequent conviction for the violation of the
20 provisions of this paragraph is a Class C2 felony offense punishable
21 by a term of imprisonment as provided for in subsections B through F
22 of Section 20M of Title 21 of the Oklahoma Statutes;
23 2. Any other controlled dangerous substance classified in
24 Schedule III, IV, V or marijuana, upon conviction, shall be guilty
